            <fr:title text="Sequences in Hausdorff space converge to at most one value">Sequences in Hausdorff space converge to at most one value</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Munkres <fr:link href="/munkres-2000-topology/" title="Topology" uri="http://localhost:8000/munkres-2000-topology/" display-uri="munkres-2000-topology" type="local">Topology</fr:link> Theorem 17.10</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">MML <fr:link href="https://mizar.uwb.edu.pl/version/current/html/frechet_2.html#T24" type="external">frechet_2:24</fr:link></fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,\mathcal {T})]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/gt-000Y/" title="Hausdorff space" uri="http://localhost:8000/gt-000Y/" display-uri="gt-000Y" type="local">Hausdorff space</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> be a convergent sequence in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a unique <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\to  x]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p><fr:link href="/nst-002J/" title="Proof by contradiction" uri="http://localhost:8000/nst-002J/" display-uri="nst-002J" type="local">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>. Assume for contradiction that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> converges to two distinct points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  X]]></fr:tex>. Then by <fr:link href="/gt-000Y/" title="Hausdorff space" uri="http://localhost:8000/gt-000Y/" display-uri="gt-000Y" type="local">Hausdorff property</fr:link>, there are disjoint open neighborhoods <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{x}\ni  x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{y}\ni  y]]></fr:tex>. By definition of <fr:link href="/gt-000O/" title="Convergence of sequence in a topological space" uri="http://localhost:8000/gt-000O/" display-uri="gt-000O" type="local">Convergence of sequence in a topological space</fr:link>, there are two positive integers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N_{x}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N_{y}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N_{x}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  U_{x}]]></fr:tex> and for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N_{y}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  U_{y}]]></fr:tex>. Setting <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N=\max (N_{x},N_{y})]]></fr:tex>, then for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  U_{x}\cap  U_{y}]]></fr:tex> which is disjoint. Hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> cannot converge to more than one point in a Hausdorff space.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
